<h2 id=3D"APIErrorHandling-Overview">Overview</h2>
<p>This page describes the error handling design, approaches and patterns t=
hat must be used&nbsp; for all Westpac Mesh API Designs.</p>
<p>APIs will always return a HTTP response code (eg. 200, 400, 500) and for=
 error scenarios (HTTP response code of 4xx or 5xx) an API will also return=
 one or more error codes which are codes assigned by the API Designer.</p>
<p>The standardised Westpac Mesh error block will be provided in all APIs w=
hich return a HTTP response code of 4xx and 5xx and also for the 'partial s=
uccess' scenario of 2xx.&nbsp; The response body for an error scenario (HTT=
P response code 4xx and 5xx) appears in the following format:</p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeHeader panelHeader pdl hide-border-bottom" style=3D"borde=
r-bottom-width: 1px;">
<b class=3D"code-title">Error</b><span class=3D"collapse-source expand-cont=
rol" style=3D"display:none;"><span class=3D"expand-control-icon icon">&nbsp=
;</span><span class=3D"expand-control-text">Expand source</span></span><spa=
n class=3D"collapse-spinner-wrapper"></span>
</div>
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl hide-toolbar">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: js; gutter: false; theme: DJango; collapse: true" data-theme=3D"DJango">{
  "result": {
    "errors": [
      {
        "code": 0,
        "message": "string",
        "details": "string"
      }
    ]
  }
}</pre>
</div>
</div>
<p>The response body for a partial success scenario (HTTP response code 2xx=
) appears in the following format:&nbsp;</p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeHeader panelHeader pdl hide-border-bottom" style=3D"borde=
r-bottom-width: 1px;">
<b class=3D"code-title">Partial Success</b><span class=3D"collapse-source e=
xpand-control" style=3D"display:none;"><span class=3D"expand-control-icon i=
con">&nbsp;</span><span class=3D"expand-control-text">Expand source</span><=
/span><span class=3D"collapse-spinner-wrapper"></span>
</div>
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl hide-toolbar">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: js; gutter: false; theme: DJango; collapse: true" data-theme=3D"DJango">{
  "data": {
    ...
  },
  "result": {
    "errors": [
      {
        "code": 0,
        "message": "string",
        "details": "string",
        "correlationKey": {
          ...
        }
      }
    ]
  }
}</pre>
</div>
</div>
<h2 id=3D"APIErrorHandling-ErrorMessagestructure">Error Message structure</=
h2>
<p>All Westpac Mesh API errors must be returned in the format specified in =
the Golden Swagger Specification, as shown above. The structure is:</p>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table class=3D"wrapped confluenceTable">
<colgroup>
<col>
<col>
<col>
</colgroup>
<tbody>
<tr>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">Error Property</th>
<th colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTh">Mandatory</th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">Description</th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">code</td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">Yes</td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><p><span class=3D"inline-comment-marker" data-re=
f=3D"9bff18fe-fb49-4aba-8001-97b016122b4f">A specific code assigned for thi=
s API to identify the type of error. This is not the HTTP response code or =
the providing system error code.</span></p><p><span class=3D"inline-comment=
-marker" data-ref=3D"9bff18fe-fb49-4aba-8001-97b016122b4f">Technical error =
codes should be &gt;=3D 10,000; business errors should be anything &lt; 10,=
000<br></span></p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><span class=3D"inline-comment-marker" data-ref=
=3D"b56a3ae6-0661-4ce1-a793-6241d118dbfa">message</span></td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">Yes</td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><p><span class=3D"inline-comment-marker" data-re=
f=3D"5100c950-1aae-4c8e-aeb1-ad9be6884202">A consumer friendly description =
of the error with context if appropriate. eg. 'Invalid customer number' or =
'mandatory customerId parameter missing or invalid' . This text is defined =
in the API and must not map a provider message.<br></span></p></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">details</td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">No</td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd"><p>Detailed description of the err=
or, usually derived from the provider error message. You may need to filter=
 out sensitive information so that it is not returned. Provider information=
 can be parsed, and can include provider error codes for context.</p></td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<p>Each API operation can respond with one or more errors.&nbsp; Errors are=
 reported as an array of error messages. For example:</p>
<div class=3D"code panel pdl" style=3D"border-width: 1px;">
<div class=3D"codeHeader panelHeader pdl hide-border-bottom" style=3D"borde=
r-bottom-width: 1px;">
<b class=3D"code-title">Sample errors</b><span class=3D"collapse-source exp=
and-control" style=3D"display:none;"><span class=3D"expand-control-icon ico=
n">&nbsp;</span><span class=3D"expand-control-text">Expand source</span></s=
pan><span class=3D"collapse-spinner-wrapper"></span>
</div>
<div class=3D"codeContent panelContent pdl hide-toolbar">
<pre class=3D"syntaxhighlighter-pre" data-syntaxhighlighter-params=3D"brush=
: js; gutter: false; theme: DJango; collapse: true" data-theme=3D"DJango">{
  "result": {
    "errors": [
      {
        "code": 400,
        "message": "mandatory customerId parameter missing or invalid",
        "details": "Field CUST_ID not supplied"
      },
      {
        "code": 400,
        "message": "mandatory accountId parameter missing or invalid",
        "details": "field ACCT_ID not supplied"
      }
    ]
  }
}</pre>
</div>
</div>
<h2 id=3D"APIErrorHandling-ErrorClassification">Error Classification</h2>
<p>At a high level there are two types of errors that can be experienced du=
ring an end to end flow from Application through to System of Record; speci=
fically a Business or Technical error.</p>
<p>A Business Error is an error that is related to the 'data' processed by =
the API and can be encountered while processing either the request or respo=
nse.&nbsp; The error code must be a number between 1 and 10000. Such errors=
 can include, but are not limited to:</p>
<ul>
<li>Missing mandatory request parameter</li>
<li>Invalid data, in request or response</li>
<li>No data found</li>
</ul>
<p>A Technical Error is an error that is related to the environment in whic=
h the API is running and prevents it from processing the data .&nbsp;The er=
ror code must be a number of <span class=3D"inline-comment-marker" data-ref=
=3D"877d9899-337c-40d2-bef4-37a8fefe81b1">10000 or greater</span>. Examples=
 are:</p>
<ul>
<li>Provider timeout</li>
<li>Provider end-point being unavailable</li>
<li>Authentication/Authorisation failure</li>
</ul>
<p>Business errors will typically be reported as a HTTP response code of 4x=
x, most often 400.&nbsp; Technical errors will typically be reported as a H=
TTP response code of 5xx, most often 500.</p>
<p>A Platform Error is an error in an intermediary in the Westpac Mesh plat=
form supporting APIs. Where a platform error occurs, and it is possible to =
control the error response to comply with this error standard, the error co=
de will be in the range from 90000-99999. This ensure that a Platform Error=
 will never have an error code conflicting with an error code indicating a =
Technical or Business Error detected in an API.</p>
<p>See&nbsp;<a href=3D"#APIErrorHandling-PlatformErrorMapping">Platform Err=
or Mapping</a> below.</p>
<h2 id=3D"APIErrorHandling-HTTPResponseCodeMapping">HTTP Response Code Mapp=
ing</h2>
<p>All Westpac Mesh API responses must return an HTTP response code to the =
consumer.</p>
<p>Successful responses will always result in an 2xx HTTP response code bei=
ng returned to the caller. <span class=3D"inline-comment-marker" data-ref=
=3D"a2a8ebc8-37f8-4ea8-945b-ee6870e49438">For unsuccessful responses the HT=
TP response code will be 4xx to indicate a client error and 5xx to indicate=
 a server error.&nbsp; As mentioned above this will generally correlate to =
business errors for 4xx response codes and technical errors for 5xx respons=
e codes.</span></p>
<h2 id=3D"APIErrorHandling-ErrorMapping">Error Mapping</h2>
<p>When errors are encountered from one or more providers for an API a deci=
sion needs to be made about which errors, if any, should be reported to the=
 consumer of the API.&nbsp; Many providers will return multiple error messa=
ges for a single root cause and it is the responsibility of the API Designe=
r to work with the Business Analyst to agree on which provider errors are '=
business important'.</p>
<p>The process for mapping the errors is as follows:</p>
<ul>
<li>Confirm whether errors being returned by the provider are actually erro=
rs and not warning or information messages</li>
<li>If they are not errors, consider whether they should be logged but trea=
t the provider call as if it was successful and return a HTTP response code=
 2xx with any appropriate data from the provider</li>
<li>Determine whether the cause of the error is bad data passed by the cons=
umer - if so, then a HTTP response code 4xx should returned=20
<ul>
<li>If expected data was not supplied or the format of the data is invalid =
use a HTTP 400 response code</li>
<li>If the data could not be found in the provider system and the identifie=
r for that data was passed in the path of the URL then use a HTTP 404 respo=
nse code (eg. GET /customers/{id})</li>
</ul></li>
<li>If the error was caused by failed processing on the server then a HTTP =
response code of 5xx should be returned</li>
<li>Once the appropriate HTTP response code has been determined you need to=
 identify the appropriate error code</li>
<li>Check the list of common error codes documented in the next section and=
 select the most appropriate one, if any</li>
<li>If a common error code is not appropriate then assign a new error <stro=
ng>code</strong>&nbsp;in the error block by allocating the next available n=
umber in the range based on the type of error (ie. business or technical)</=
li>
<li>Provide an easily understood description of the error in the <strong>me=
ssage</strong> element of the error block - this text will be decided by th=
e API Designer and should NOT be simply mapped from a provider error messag=
e=20
<ul>
<li>Note that this text need not be worded so that it can be displayed on a=
 UI as it is the UI designer's responsibility to provide user friendly erro=
r messages on the UI</li>
</ul></li>
<li>Map the provider's error message to the <strong>details</strong> elemen=
t of the error block=20
<ul>
<li>Be careful that you do not expose sensitive data such as customer detai=
ls from provider systems</li>
<li>Provide the minimal amount of information that would assist troubleshoo=
ting the error</li>
</ul></li>
</ul>
<h2 id=3D"APIErrorHandling-Additionalerrorhandlingconsiderations">Additiona=
l error handling considerations</h2>
<p>Error handling can be a fairly straightforward process for atomic APIs (=
those which invoke a single provider) but composite APIs&nbsp;(those which =
invoke more than one provider) require more thought.&nbsp; For composite AP=
Is you need to consider whether a failure in a call to one of the providers=
 should be considered a failure or a partial success.&nbsp; Refer to the <a=
 href=3D"https://confluence.srv.westpac.com.au/display/mesh/Pattern+6%3A+AP=
I+Design+-+Partial+Success" rel=3D"nofollow">Partial Success Pattern</a> fo=
r more details.&nbsp; The API architect should provide direction on whether=
 partial success should be supported in the API.</p>
<p>Partial success may also need to be supported where the API accepts a li=
st of objects, such as accounts, to be processed.&nbsp; It is possible that=
 one or more of these objects may not be able to be processed due to backen=
d errors or bad data supplied by the caller.</p>
<p>When designing the errors in your API , put yourself in the shoes of a c=
onsumer and think about the types of errors you would want to know about.&n=
bsp; For example, you might want to be able to distinguish between technica=
l errors which identify that a provider cannot be contacted and where a pro=
vider is unable to return a response within a reasonable time period, other=
wise referred to as a timeout.&nbsp; If you are creating a new customer and=
 receive an error advising that the API was unable to contact the provider =
you can confidently retry the call without being concerned about creating a=
 duplicate customer.&nbsp; However, if you receive a timeout then you canno=
t be sure that the provider has not created the customer.&nbsp;</p>
<p>It is expected that over time we will build APIs which call other APIs w=
hich in turn call providers or other APIs and errors will be reported at ea=
ch level in the call stack.&nbsp; It is important that the occurrence of an=
 error is propagated up the call stack (so that consumers know that an erro=
r has occurred) but the error at each level must NOT be blindly propagated =
up the call stack.&nbsp; You can include provider error details from the do=
wnstream call in your API's specific error block to aid in troubleshooting.=
&nbsp; More thorough investigation can be achieved by reviewing the API log=
s for all calls with the same 'x-appCorrelationId' header value.</p>
<h2 id=3D"APIErrorHandling-CommonProviderErrorMapping">Common Provider Erro=
r Mapping</h2>
<p>APIs will integrate to a wide variety of providers who will invariably d=
efine their own set of error codes but there will be a common subset of err=
ors that all providers will produce. The following table contains a list of=
 those common errors and the recommended representation of them.<strong><br=
></strong></p>
<h5 id=3D"APIErrorHandling-ErrorMapping.1">Error <span class=3D"inline-comm=
ent-marker" data-ref=3D"35cdf636-4a7b-4e80-9410-9f06c152a003">Mapping</span=
></h5>
<div class=3D"table-wrap">
<table class=3D"wrapped confluenceTable">
<colgroup>
<col>
<col style=3D"width: 267.0px;">
<col style=3D"width: 145.0px;">
<col style=3D"width: 94.0px;">
<col style=3D"width: 124.0px;">
<col>
<col style=3D"width: 303.0px;">
<col>
</colgroup>
<tbody>
<tr>
<th colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTh">Provider Error Code</th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">Provider Error Message/Description/Use Case</th>
<th colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTh">Error Type</th>
<th class=3D"confluenceTh">HTTP Response Code</th>
<th colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTh">Error Code</th>
<th colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTh">Error Message</th>
<th colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTh">Error Details</th>
<th colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTh">Comments</th>
</tr>
<tr>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd"><br></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">Host Unavailable</td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">Technical</td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);">500</span></t=
d>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">10001</td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd"><p>Unable to contact provider {pro=
vider name}</p><p><br></p></td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">Map provider error details</td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd"><br></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd"><br></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">Host Timeout</td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">Technical</td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">500</td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">10002</td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">Timeout error encountered for provider {provider=
 name}</td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><p><span>Map provider error details</span></p></=
td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><br></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd"><br></td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">Failed Authentication</td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">Technical</td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">500</td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">10003</td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">Unable to authenticate with the pr=
ovider</td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd"><br></td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">APIs should not require consumers =
to pass credentials to downstream providers as the API should authenticate =
to the provider itself. Thus, this error will only occur if the API's crede=
ntials for the provider are incorrect.</td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd"><br></td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">Failed Authorisation</td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">Technical</td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">500</td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">10004</td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">Provider is unable to authorise th=
e action requested by the API</td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd"><br></td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd"><span>APIs should not require cons=
umers to pass credentials to downstream providers as the API should authent=
icate to the provider itself. Thus, this error will only occur if the API's=
 credentials for the provider are incorrect.</span></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd"><br></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">Missing mandatory Field</td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">Business</td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">400</td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">1</td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd">The mandatory field {field name} was not supplie=
d</td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><p><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);"><span>Map =
provider error details only if the error was generated by the provider - mo=
st of these errors will arise due to validation within the API itself</span=
><br></span></p></td>
<td class=3D"confluenceTd"><br></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd"><br></td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">Invalid Data</td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">Business</td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">400</td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">2</td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">The field {field name} contains in=
valid data according to its specified format</td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd"><span style=3D"color: rgb(0,0,0);"=
>Map provider error details only if the error was generated by the provider=
 - most of these errors will arise due to validation within the API itself<=
/span></td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd"><br></td>
</tr>
<tr>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd"><br></td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">No data found</td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">Business</td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">404 or 400</td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">3</td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">Unable to locate a {resource} with=
 the specified identifier</td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd"><p>i.e. Customer not found, or Acc=
ount not found.</p><p><span style=3D"color: rgb(255,0,0);"><span style=3D"c=
olor: rgb(0,0,0);">If error contains meaningful details, that the consumer =
will understand, the pass-through provider error message</span></span></p><=
/td>
<td colspan=3D"1" class=3D"confluenceTd">A 404 HTTP response code should on=
ly be returned if the resource identifier is provided in the URL path (eg. =
/customers/{customerId} otherwise return a 400 HTTP response code.</td>
</tr>
</tbody>
</table>
</div>
<p><br></p>
<h2 id=3D"APIErrorHandling-PlatformErrorMapping">Platform Error Mapping</h2=
>
<p>Platform Error are detected in an intermediary provided by the Westpac M=
esh Platform (a gateway, reverse proxy, forward proxy, or framework-provide=
d HTTP handler or filter). The following table contains a list of platform =
errors.<strong><br></strong></p>
